-You give him lidocaine?

128
00:11:31,995 --> 00:11:32,791
100's gone in.

129
00:11:32,995 --> 00:11:34,314
Buzz him again at 300.

130
00:11:36,555 --> 00:11:38,147
-Still nothing.
-Start compression.

131
00:11:38,315 --> 00:11:39,225
Kill the alarm!

132
00:11:43,955 --> 00:11:45,468
Hold up. It's not working.

133
00:11:45,675 --> 00:11:48,030
Got to open him.
How long to go back on?

134
00:11:48,355 --> 00:11:49,674
It'll take me 10 minutes.

135
00:11:50,035 --> 00:11:51,468
Come on! Nothing.

136
00:11:51,795 --> 00:11:52,671
Knife.

137
00:12:00,795 --> 00:12:02,831
Internal paddles. Charge to 20.

138
00:12:03,555 --> 00:12:04,385
Ready.

139
00:12:04,915 --> 00:12:05,791
Hit it.

140
00:12:08,035 --> 00:12:09,309
Go to 30.

141
00:12:10,155 --> 00:12:10,985
Hit it.

142
00:12:11,355 --> 00:12:12,504
No response.

143
00:12:13,235 --> 00:12:14,873
Tom, I got to get back on bypass here.

144
00:12:15,155 --> 00:12:16,793
Almost there.
Give me 7 more minutes.

145
00:12:17,115 --> 00:12:17,945
Come on.

146
00:12:20,795 --> 00:12:21,910
Don't do this.

147
00:12:23,875 --> 00:12:24,705
He's going.

148
00:12:25,395 --> 00:12:26,384
He's not going anywhere.

149
00:12:36,275 --> 00:12:38,027
Come on, don't do this!

150
00:12:40,635 --> 00:12:41,909
Damn it, come on!

151
00:12:43,955 --> 00:12:44,990
Tom!

152
00:12:46,675 --> 00:12:48,108
Come on!

153
00:13:10,155 --> 00:13:11,429
Mrs. Balford?

154
00:13:12,635 --> 00:13:13,829
Where's the doctor?

155
00:13:15,355 --> 00:13:17,391
-I'm the doctor.
-I'm sorry.

156
00:13:19,355 --> 00:13:20,583
I operated on your husband.

157
00:13:21,195 --> 00:13:22,423
How is he?

158
00:13:24,875 --> 00:13:25,864
He didn't survive.

159
00:13:29,275 --> 00:13:30,105
What?

160
00:13:32,555 --> 00:13:34,989
We were able to restore
blood flow to the heart...

161
00:13:35,355 --> 00:13:38,347
...but he developed a lethal arrhythmia
and we couldn't resuscitate him.

162
00:13:38,715 --> 00:13:42,185
Wait. I'm sorry, I don't understand.
A what?

163
00:13:45,715 --> 00:13:46,704
I'm sorry.

164
00:13:52,875 --> 00:13:54,433
Excuse me. I'm sorry.

165
00:13:54,995 --> 00:13:56,633
What did you say?

166
00:13:59,475 --> 00:14:00,669
What?

167
00:14:01,995 --> 00:14:03,189
Oh, my God!

168
00:14:31,795 --> 00:14:34,389
On the table, on my table. I'm sorry.

169
00:14:34,675 --> 00:14:36,108
I'm sorry.

170
00:14:38,635 --> 00:14:40,751
I'm sorry. What happened?
What happened?

171
00:14:40,995 --> 00:14:43,031
A graft occlusion? What?

172
00:14:45,075 --> 00:14:47,509
It was textbook. It was textbook.

173
00:14:53,915 --> 00:14:55,348
I'm so sorry.

174
00:14:58,035 --> 00:14:59,707
The room got so big.
I was so small.

175
00:14:59,955 --> 00:15:01,911
How did I get so small?

176
00:15:02,795 --> 00:15:03,944
I should've gone back on.

177
00:15:04,315 --> 00:15:06,545
I should've massaged longer.

178
00:15:06,835 --> 00:15:09,793
I should've gone back on.
Massaged longer. I lost it.

179
00:15:12,115 --> 00:15:13,594
I lost it.

180
00:15:31,595 --> 00:15:33,586
Have you ever been seen, Cassiel?

181
00:15:34,995 --> 00:15:35,871
You're looking at me.

182
00:15:36,515 --> 00:15:40,508
No, not by me, and not
by the dying or the delirious.

183
00:15:41,235 --> 00:15:42,827
Have you ever been seen...

184
00:15:43,795 --> 00:15:45,433
...like you were a man?

185
00:15:46,555 --> 00:15:50,707
In a diner once, a blind woman
turned to me all of a sudden...

186
00:15:51,035 --> 00:15:52,832
...and asked me to pass her the mustard.

187
00:15:53,875 --> 00:15:56,947
-But she was blind.
-But she knew I was there.

188
00:15:57,915 --> 00:16:00,907
That doctor in the operating room...

189
00:16:02,675 --> 00:16:04,472
...she looked right at me.

190
00:16:04,875 --> 00:16:07,309
She didn't see you, Seth.
She can't see you.

191
00:16:07,595 --> 00:16:09,904
No one can see you
unless you want them to.

192
00:16:10,635 --> 00:16:12,034
And if I want her to?

193
00:16:13,395 --> 00:16:14,510
Why do you want her to?

194
00:16:16,395 --> 00:16:17,623
To help her.

195
00:16:18,515 --> 00:16:19,470
Open it!

196
00:16:19,755 --> 00:16:21,074
Open it now!

197
00:16:21,675 --> 00:16:22,869
Everybody down!

198
00:16:24,955 --> 00:16:26,593
Do it! Do it!

199
00:16:26,875 --> 00:16:28,593
Shit! Just give him the money.

200
00:16:28,915 --> 00:16:31,349
Did I leave the lights on?
I left the lights on.

201
00:16:31,675 --> 00:16:33,427
I should have gone to Ralphs.

202
00:16:34,075 --> 00:16:36,350
-Do it!
-Relax. I'm doing it, okay?

203
00:16:37,715 --> 00:16:39,387
I never saw the Grand Canyon.

204
00:16:39,675 --> 00:16:41,154
I'll never see my grandkids again.

205
00:16:42,955 --> 00:16:44,308
What am I doing?

206
00:16:45,235 --> 00:16:46,873
Just be cool. Be cool.

207
00:16:51,555 --> 00:16:52,385
Be cool, man.

208
00:16:53,075 --> 00:16:54,190
Be cool.

209
00:16:59,115 --> 00:17:00,343
Holy shit!

210
00:17:02,675 --> 00:17:04,154
They don't need to see us.

211
00:17:22,715 --> 00:17:24,148
You're early.

212
00:17:55,915 --> 00:17:56,984
What's going on?

213
00:17:57,315 --> 00:17:58,953
Ferris was looking for you.

214
00:18:10,795 --> 00:18:12,228
Don't I have a mitral valve to do?

215
00:18:12,435 --> 00:18:13,993
They canceled it.

216
00:18:14,755 --> 00:18:15,551
Who canceled it?

217
00:18:15,715 --> 00:18:16,591
Sheffield.

218
00:18:17,035 --> 00:18:18,229
Why are you telling me?

219
00:18:18,555 --> 00:18:19,385
He was busy.

220
00:18:19,595 --> 00:18:20,869
He was chickenshit.

221
00:18:21,155 --> 00:18:22,952
-Maggie, you're sick.
-I'm not sick.

222
00:18:23,235 --> 00:18:24,714
You're sick.
You can't operate.

223
00:18:24,995 --> 00:18:27,509
They've rescheduled for Monday.
An elective valve, no big deal.

224
00:18:27,795 --> 00:18:30,946
It is unprofessional, and it
embarrasses me in front of my staff.

225
00:18:35,315 --> 00:18:37,033
I saw the chart on Balford.

226
00:18:38,475 --> 00:18:40,227
I'm on the committee.
It's on review.

227
00:18:40,915 --> 00:18:42,792
-It wasn't your fault.
-I know.

228
00:18:43,035 --> 00:18:44,354
Then what's the problem?

229
00:18:48,435 --> 00:18:49,663
I don't know.

230
00:18:50,915 --> 00:18:52,746
You put up a terrific fight.

231
00:18:55,795 --> 00:18:57,592
We fight for people's lives, right?

232
00:19:00,315 --> 00:19:02,704
Don't you ever wonder who
it is we're fighting with?

233
00:19:07,075 --> 00:19:08,633
So I'm crazy and chemically imbalanced.

234
00:19:08,875 --> 00:19:10,388
You're tired.

235
00:19:11,515 --> 00:19:12,948
You have moments.

236
00:19:14,835 --> 00:19:15,870
Why didn't you call me?

237
00:19:18,555 --> 00:19:20,466
Because I never sleep
when you stay over.

238
00:19:20,715 --> 00:19:22,592
You never sleep whether
I stay over or not.

239
00:19:24,755 --> 00:19:25,870
You're good.

240
00:19:26,195 --> 00:19:27,389
You know it.

241
00:19:27,835 --> 00:19:29,871
Come back Monday
and get back on the horse.

242
00:19:31,555 --> 00:19:32,385
Doctor?

243
00:19:38,675 --> 00:19:39,710
I'll see you.

244
00:20:03,355 --> 00:20:06,711
"As I walk along the stony shore
of the pond in my shirtsleeves.... "

245
00:20:06,995 --> 00:20:09,509
"...Amazon basin in the north,
once an island sea.... "

246
00:20:09,795 --> 00:20:12,309
"The highest truth on the
subject remains unsaid...

247
00:20:12,595 --> 00:20:14,347
...probably cannot be said.

248
00:20:14,595 --> 00:20:18,554
For all that we say is the far-off
remembering of the intuition... "

249
00:20:18,995 --> 00:20:22,431
"...she begins to pull away from
the awareness she had once.... "

250
00:20:27,515 --> 00:20:28,914
"Commencing search. "
Searching my soul.

251
00:20:29,235 --> 00:20:31,954
What happened to the cards?
You could touch the cards.

252
00:20:32,315 --> 00:20:34,351
She's been looking
at me for half an hour.

253
00:20:34,635 --> 00:20:35,954
Maybe if I just hang here....

254
00:20:36,315 --> 00:20:40,103
"This is a delicious evening,
when the whole body's one sense.... "

255
00:20:40,475 --> 00:20:43,865
What if I screamed?
What if I just screamed right now?

256
00:20:45,595 --> 00:20:47,984
"When a woman decides to sleep
with a man.... "

257
00:20:49,795 --> 00:20:52,434
"You knew there would always
be a spring...

258
00:20:52,715 --> 00:20:56,947
...as you knew the river
would flow again after it was frozen.

259
00:20:57,315 --> 00:21:00,785
When the cold rains kept on
and killed the spring...

260
00:21:01,155 --> 00:21:05,467
...it was as though a young person
had died for no reason. "

261
00:21:40,035 --> 00:21:42,754
All right, they have rescheduled
the operation for Monday.

262
00:21:43,035 --> 00:21:44,104
What happened yesterday?

263
00:21:44,475 --> 00:21:45,988
They had a golf tournament.

264
00:21:46,275 --> 00:21:47,674
Who knows with these people?

265
00:21:47,955 --> 00:21:49,070
Good morning, Mr. Messinger.

266
00:21:49,435 --> 00:21:51,824
The "G" is soft, like "messenger".

267
00:21:54,315 --> 00:21:55,384
What's on your lip?

268
00:21:55,795 --> 00:21:58,025
What? Am I slobbering here?

269
00:22:02,995 --> 00:22:05,463
-Where did you get that?
-What am l, a prisoner?

270
00:22:05,755 --> 00:22:08,428
You want to get well, or
you want Ben & Jerry's?

271
00:22:08,795 --> 00:22:10,148
This operation is a big deal.

272
00:22:10,875 --> 00:22:12,228
Continue to eat like this...

273
00:22:13,155 --> 00:22:15,350
...and you might as well skip it.
Save the 30 grand.

274
00:22:15,595 --> 00:22:19,508
If you'd have performed the operation
yesterday like you were supposed to...

275
00:22:19,835 --> 00:22:23,066
...I'd be sucking carrots through
a straw in my arm. What happened?

276
00:22:23,795 --> 00:22:26,150
Circumstances were not optimal
for the procedure.

277
00:22:26,515 --> 00:22:30,554
I ain't "the procedure". My name is
Nathan Messinger and I'm right here.

278
00:23:51,875 --> 00:23:54,230
Hello, hello, hello....

279
00:23:56,835 --> 00:23:59,508
Floating, floating. Don't pop it.
Don't pop it!

280
00:24:01,995 --> 00:24:04,907
Do you know the Muffin Man,
the Muffin Man, the Muffin Man?

281
00:24:48,795 --> 00:24:49,591
Hi, Anne.

282
00:24:49,835 --> 00:24:51,234
What are you doing here?

283
00:24:51,875 --> 00:24:53,433
I was on my way up to x-ray...

284
00:24:53,715 --> 00:24:55,785
...and I thought I'd stop in and just...

285
00:24:56,915 --> 00:24:57,870
...hide.

286
00:24:58,795 --> 00:24:59,830
From what?

287
00:25:01,955 --> 00:25:03,434
I should've gone into pediatrics.

288
00:25:03,795 --> 00:25:04,671
Oh, no.

289
00:25:05,035 --> 00:25:07,549
Every guy you meet
is either married or a gyno.

290
00:25:07,795 --> 00:25:10,593
Never date a man who knows more
about your vagina than you do.

291
00:25:13,475 --> 00:25:15,227
Poor little guy.

292
00:25:19,435 --> 00:25:21,187
He never stops crying.

293
00:25:21,435 --> 00:25:23,551
-What's wrong with him?
-No insurance.

294
00:25:25,195 --> 00:25:27,993
Found him in a dumpster
behind the House of Pies.

295
00:25:28,435 --> 00:25:30,153
We worked him up the wazoo
for everything...

296
00:25:30,395 --> 00:25:33,228
...from drug exposure to diabetes.
We got nothing.

297
00:25:34,395 --> 00:25:35,464
May I?

298
00:25:47,955 --> 00:25:49,183
Did you do an ultrasound?

299
00:25:49,435 --> 00:25:51,187
-You hear a murmur?
-Worth a shot.

300
00:25:52,355 --> 00:25:54,107
Okay, baby.

301
00:25:57,195 --> 00:25:59,834
So what are you hiding from?

302
00:26:01,795 --> 00:26:03,513
My patient's wife.

303
00:26:04,475 --> 00:26:07,353
She wants me to tell her that her
husband is going to be okay...

304
00:26:07,675 --> 00:26:10,189
...and that I have every confidence...

305
00:26:10,995 --> 00:26:12,110
...and I don't.

306
00:26:12,475 --> 00:26:15,308
And after all this time,
and after all this work...

307
00:26:15,555 --> 00:26:17,864
...I suddenly have this feeling that...

308
00:26:19,315 --> 00:26:21,749
...none of this is in my hands.
Nothing.

309
00:26:22,995 --> 00:26:24,269
And if it isn't...

310
00:26:24,515 --> 00:26:26,073
...what do I do with that?

311
00:27:22,955 --> 00:27:24,183
Excuse me.

312
00:27:31,835 --> 00:27:33,234
Are you a visitor?

313
00:27:34,875 --> 00:27:35,830
Yes.

314
00:27:36,955 --> 00:27:39,515
Visiting hours have been
over since 8:00.

315
00:27:40,235 --> 00:27:41,907
Why do they have that?

316
00:27:42,435 --> 00:27:43,265
What?

317
00:27:43,475 --> 00:27:44,590
Hours.

318
00:27:45,715 --> 00:27:48,104
Doesn't it help the patient
to be visited?

319
00:27:50,435 --> 00:27:52,266
Who are you visiting?
Mr. Messinger?

320
00:27:52,515 --> 00:27:53,664
Right now?

321
00:27:57,755 --> 00:27:58,665
You.

322
00:28:02,755 --> 00:28:04,074
I don't need a visitor.

323
00:28:04,315 --> 00:28:05,430
You're not ill?

324
00:28:05,675 --> 00:28:06,585
No.

325
00:28:08,515 --> 00:28:10,471
I'm one of the doctors here.

326
00:28:13,155 --> 00:28:14,634
Are you in despair?

327
00:28:19,075 --> 00:28:20,827
I lost a patient.

328
00:28:21,595 --> 00:28:23,426
You did everything you could?

329
00:28:24,795 --> 00:28:27,355
I was holding his heart
in my hand when he died.

330
00:28:28,515 --> 00:28:30,073
Then he wasn't alone.

331
00:28:30,475 --> 00:28:31,624
Yes, he was.

332
00:28:31,915 --> 00:28:32,950
People die.

333
00:28:33,195 --> 00:28:34,230
Not on my table.

334
00:28:34,475 --> 00:28:36,864
People die when their bodies give out.

335
00:28:37,155 --> 00:28:40,511
It's my job to keep their bodies from
giving out. Or what am I doing here?

336
00:28:40,755 --> 00:28:42,552
It wasn't your fault, Maggie.

337
00:28:42,835 --> 00:28:44,268
I wanted him to live.

338
00:28:44,515 --> 00:28:45,868
He is living.

339
00:28:46,435 --> 00:28:48,346
Just not the way you think.

340
00:28:56,115 --> 00:28:57,673
I don't believe in that.

341
00:28:57,915 --> 00:29:00,907
Some things are true
whether you believe in them or not.

342
00:29:02,555 --> 00:29:04,068
How did you know my name?

343
00:29:08,195 --> 00:29:09,423
What's yours?

344
00:29:11,355 --> 00:29:12,504
Seth.

345
00:29:20,635 --> 00:29:22,353
You better get out of here, Seth...

346
00:29:22,595 --> 00:29:25,189
...or security's going to think
you're a psych patient.

347
00:30:34,595 --> 00:30:36,711
-Where are we?
-Down a liter.

348
00:30:38,315 --> 00:30:39,065
Suction.

349
00:30:39,995 --> 00:30:44,910
I am stuck on Band-Aid brand
'Cause Band-Aid's stuck on me

350
00:30:50,595 --> 00:30:54,952
No dying now, Mr. Messinger. Not until
you give me Seth's phone number.

351
00:30:56,315 --> 00:31:00,866
I am stuck on Band-Aid brand
'Cause Band-Aid's stuck on me

352
00:31:27,475 --> 00:31:29,067
Those eyes.

353
00:31:29,755 --> 00:31:31,666
The way he looked...

354
00:31:32,155 --> 00:31:34,146
...right down into me.

355
00:31:36,115 --> 00:31:37,389
Seth.

356
00:31:38,795 --> 00:31:41,025
What kind of name is Seth?

357
00:33:37,795 --> 00:33:39,194
I thought you'd be here.

358
00:33:40,475 --> 00:33:41,544
Salty.

359
00:33:41,995 --> 00:33:44,384
My transplant tanked at 2 a.m.

360
00:33:45,875 --> 00:33:47,069
You okay?

361
00:33:53,755 --> 00:33:55,552
You might want to return this.

362
00:33:59,515 --> 00:34:03,110
That part about the spring?
"You knew there'd always be a spring".

363
00:34:03,875 --> 00:34:05,547
How did you know that...?

364
00:34:05,835 --> 00:34:07,871
What? I didn't give you this book.

365
00:34:11,875 --> 00:34:12,785
You didn't?

366
00:34:13,315 --> 00:34:14,464
Where'd you get it?

367
00:34:25,955 --> 00:34:29,072
Hi. I'm a physician, and I think
a patient left that in my office.

368
00:34:29,315 --> 00:34:32,193
-Can you tell me who checked it out?
-I can't tell you who.

369
00:34:32,435 --> 00:34:34,312
I can tell you when.

370
00:34:35,795 --> 00:34:37,353
All right, give me 5 minutes.

371
00:35:07,955 --> 00:35:09,354
Hello, Maggie.

372
00:35:11,675 --> 00:35:13,393
It's nice to see you again.

373
00:35:13,795 --> 00:35:15,433
It's weird to see you again.

374
00:35:16,115 --> 00:35:17,434
Weird is nice.

375
00:35:21,155 --> 00:35:22,224
You like Hemingway?

376
00:35:23,875 --> 00:35:25,433
Yeah, I'm starting to.

377
00:35:31,075 --> 00:35:31,951
May I?

378
00:35:34,595 --> 00:35:37,553
"As I ate the oysters with their
strong taste of the sea...

379
00:35:37,915 --> 00:35:39,951
...and their faint metallic taste...

380
00:35:40,475 --> 00:35:42,705
...as I drank their cold liquid
from each shell...

381
00:35:42,955 --> 00:35:45,708
...and washed it down
with the crisp taste of the wine...

382
00:35:46,035 --> 00:35:47,787
...I lost the empty feeling...

383
00:35:48,155 --> 00:35:50,032
...and began to be happy".

384
00:35:50,835 --> 00:35:53,224
He never forgets to describe
how things taste.

385
00:35:54,675 --> 00:35:55,949
I like that.

386
00:35:58,515 --> 00:36:00,392
Do you come here a lot?

387
00:36:01,035 --> 00:36:02,263
I live here.

388
00:36:03,755 --> 00:36:05,188
What do you do?

389
00:36:05,475 --> 00:36:06,385
Read.

390
00:36:06,635 --> 00:36:08,830
No, I mean, your work.

391
00:36:10,115 --> 00:36:11,434
I'm a messenger.

392
00:36:13,515 --> 00:36:15,506
What kind of messenger?
A bike messenger?

393
00:36:15,955 --> 00:36:18,264
No, I'm a messenger of God.

394
00:36:20,315 --> 00:36:21,464
Got a message for me?

395
00:36:22,515 --> 00:36:23,948
I already gave it to you.

396
00:36:24,195 --> 00:36:28,074
Did you use my pager? I usually don't
get my messages unless you beep me.

397
00:36:29,155 --> 00:36:32,306
You've definitely been beeped.

398
00:36:34,475 --> 00:36:36,511
-How is Messinger?
-He's good.

399
00:36:36,835 --> 00:36:38,553
The operation went really well.

400
00:36:39,075 --> 00:36:41,145
-It was a good day.
-It was.

401
00:36:41,395 --> 00:36:43,625
Yeah, I didn't kill anybody today.

402
00:36:44,195 --> 00:36:46,834
-You're an excellent doctor.
-How do you know?

403
00:36:47,715 --> 00:36:48,784
I have a feeling.

404
00:36:49,155 --> 00:36:51,225
That's pretty flimsy evidence.

405
00:36:52,115 --> 00:36:53,150
Close your eyes.

406
00:36:55,955 --> 00:36:57,354
It's just for a moment.

407
00:37:16,755 --> 00:37:18,188
What am I doing?

408
00:37:20,315 --> 00:37:22,465
You're touching me.

409
00:37:23,435 --> 00:37:24,788
Touch.

410
00:37:26,315 --> 00:37:27,543
How do you know?

411
00:37:29,035 --> 00:37:30,627
Because I feel it.

412
00:37:39,075 --> 00:37:40,633
You should trust that.

413
00:37:41,355 --> 00:37:43,073
You don't trust it enough.

414
00:37:55,235 --> 00:37:57,351
-Let's go somewhere.
-Where?

415
00:37:57,875 --> 00:37:58,785
I don't care.

416
00:37:59,955 --> 00:38:01,183
What do you want to do?

417
00:38:01,955 --> 00:38:03,434
Anything.

418
00:38:47,075 --> 00:38:48,633
What's that like?

419
00:38:51,315 --> 00:38:52,907
What's it taste like?

420
00:38:53,355 --> 00:38:54,947
Describe it. Like Hemingway.

421
00:38:57,075 --> 00:38:58,986
Well, it tastes like...

422
00:38:59,955 --> 00:39:01,149
...a pear.

423
00:39:01,875 --> 00:39:03,945
You don't know what a pear tastes like?

424
00:39:04,635 --> 00:39:07,149
I don't know what a pear
tastes like to you.

425
00:39:13,155 --> 00:39:14,474
Sweet...

426
00:39:14,835 --> 00:39:16,109
...juicy.

427
00:39:17,635 --> 00:39:20,388
Soft on your tongue.
Grainy...

428
00:39:20,755 --> 00:39:23,508
...like sugary sand that
dissolves in your mouth.

429
00:39:27,155 --> 00:39:28,383
How's that?

430
00:39:31,515 --> 00:39:32,914
It's perfect.

431
00:39:49,635 --> 00:39:53,992
The first time I looked in a microscope,
I knew I wanted to be a doctor.

432
00:39:57,235 --> 00:39:59,066
Okay, let me have your hand.

433
00:39:59,675 --> 00:40:00,790
What for?

434
00:40:01,075 --> 00:40:02,747
We'll take a look at your blood.

435
00:40:03,755 --> 00:40:05,427
Not a possibility.

436
00:40:08,675 --> 00:40:09,790
Men.

437
00:40:10,035 --> 00:40:12,265
I suppose you know a woman's
threshold of pain...

438
00:40:12,515 --> 00:40:14,346
...is 9 times higher than a man's.

439
00:40:24,995 --> 00:40:26,394
Take a look at that.

440
00:40:29,955 --> 00:40:31,946
That's bright.

441
00:40:36,915 --> 00:40:38,189
That's me.

442
00:40:39,155 --> 00:40:40,349
All those cells.

443
00:40:41,715 --> 00:40:43,387
That's all you are.

444
00:40:45,555 --> 00:40:47,785
That and all the space in between.

445
00:40:48,995 --> 00:40:50,986
If this is all you are...

446
00:40:51,235 --> 00:40:52,907
...these cells...

447
00:40:53,795 --> 00:40:55,945
...then when they die, that's the end.

448
00:40:57,195 --> 00:40:58,913
I don't know. I think so.

449
00:41:00,835 --> 00:41:02,507
How do you explain it?

450
00:41:02,755 --> 00:41:03,710
What?

451
00:41:05,355 --> 00:41:07,425
The enduring myth of Heaven.

452
00:41:12,315 --> 00:41:14,590
I used to think that I had it
all figured out.

453
00:41:14,835 --> 00:41:15,904
But you didn't?

454
00:41:16,315 --> 00:41:17,350
No.

455
00:41:22,555 --> 00:41:26,343
Because something happened
in my O.R. and I got...

456
00:41:26,835 --> 00:41:30,191
...this jolt. I got this feeling
that there's something...

457
00:41:30,635 --> 00:41:34,025
...bigger out there. Something bigger
than me, bigger than you, and it....

458
00:41:35,595 --> 00:41:37,233
Does that sound crazy?

459
00:41:37,955 --> 00:41:38,990
No.

460
00:41:40,315 --> 00:41:42,909
I couldn't fix him.
I did everything right...

461
00:41:43,155 --> 00:41:44,827
...and I couldn't fix him.

462
00:41:45,955 --> 00:41:47,673
That's not supposed to happen.

463
00:41:50,315 --> 00:41:51,668
And I...

464
00:41:52,195 --> 00:41:53,514
You cried.

465
00:41:56,635 --> 00:41:57,670
Yeah.

466
00:41:59,715 --> 00:42:02,673
-Why do people cry?
-What do you mean?

467
00:42:03,355 --> 00:42:05,744
I mean, what happens physically?

468
00:42:09,395 --> 00:42:12,831
Tear ducts operate on a normal basis
to lubricate and protect the eye.

469
00:42:13,075 --> 00:42:16,226
When you have an emotion,
they overact and create tears.

470
00:42:16,475 --> 00:42:18,386
Why? Why do they overact?

471
00:42:21,075 --> 00:42:22,394
I don't know.

472
00:42:25,035 --> 00:42:26,946
Maybe emotion becomes so intense...

473
00:42:27,195 --> 00:42:28,992
...your body just can't contain it.

474
00:42:29,235 --> 00:42:32,750
Your mind and your feelings
become too powerful.

475
00:42:32,995 --> 00:42:34,667
Your body weeps.

476
00:42:40,635 --> 00:42:41,670
I have to go.

477
00:42:41,955 --> 00:42:43,866
I got to go. Stay right here.

478
00:42:44,395 --> 00:42:45,623
Don't go anywhere.

479
00:42:46,115 --> 00:42:47,548
Stay right there.

480
00:43:07,755 --> 00:43:09,154
-Get the tube out.
-He can't breathe.

481
00:43:09,435 --> 00:43:11,187
It's because the tube is blocked.

482
00:43:22,835 --> 00:43:24,188
How you feeling?

483
00:43:24,515 --> 00:43:26,312
Ready to hit the waves.

484
00:43:26,555 --> 00:43:29,069
I'm afraid your bodysurfing
days are over.

485
00:43:31,555 --> 00:43:35,434
You got a mean tattoo going there.
What does your wife think of that?

486
00:43:36,595 --> 00:43:38,347
That is my wife.

487
00:43:47,075 --> 00:43:49,225
Check his vitals every 15.

488
00:44:05,715 --> 00:44:07,433
I can't see you,
but I know you're there.

489
00:44:14,995 --> 00:44:17,031
Go back and tell them
that I'm not going.

490
00:44:18,635 --> 00:44:20,034
Not yet.

491
00:44:47,835 --> 00:44:49,188
Where have you been?

492
00:44:49,755 --> 00:44:52,110
Oh, shit. I totally forgot dinner.

493
00:44:52,435 --> 00:44:53,663
Dinner?

494
00:44:54,115 --> 00:44:55,230
With who?

495
00:44:58,995 --> 00:45:01,748
A guy I met. I bumped into him
and we got something to eat.

496
00:45:01,995 --> 00:45:03,508
Did you pack my backpack?

497
00:45:04,355 --> 00:45:05,629
What else?

498
00:45:06,875 --> 00:45:08,069
We talked...

499
00:45:08,315 --> 00:45:10,385
...and then I got beeped
and he disappeared.

500
00:45:10,635 --> 00:45:11,863
Why did you pack my backpack?

501
00:45:12,355 --> 00:45:13,993
Earl, what are you doing?

502
00:45:14,235 --> 00:45:16,795
I thought we'd fly up to Tahoe,
use your uncle's cabin...

503
00:45:17,075 --> 00:45:18,303
...maybe do a little hiking.

504
00:45:19,875 --> 00:45:20,830
What?

505
00:45:23,635 --> 00:45:25,432
God. Is it...?

506
00:45:25,755 --> 00:45:26,904
Maggie, it's just a tick.

507
00:45:27,395 --> 00:45:30,148
-Get a match.
-We're not going to burn him, Jordan.

508
00:45:30,395 --> 00:45:32,226
It'll have to back out.
Can't leave the head in.

509
00:45:32,475 --> 00:45:35,467
-We can't just be burning tick heads.
-Then get some alcohol.

510
00:45:35,715 --> 00:45:36,545
I don't have any.

511
00:45:36,795 --> 00:45:38,945
-You don't have any alcohol?
-I don't operate here.

512
00:45:39,195 --> 00:45:40,628
How about some olive oil?

513
00:45:43,275 --> 00:45:44,788
Which kind? Jalapeno or rosemary?

514
00:45:45,635 --> 00:45:46,988
Rosemary.

515
00:45:48,195 --> 00:45:51,710
So what did you and your friend...
What did you say his name was?

516
00:45:53,395 --> 00:45:54,350
Seth.

517
00:45:54,595 --> 00:45:56,392
What did you two talk about?

518
00:45:58,035 --> 00:45:59,184
Dying.

519
00:46:01,555 --> 00:46:05,070
Come on, we deal with life and death
every day. Why can't we talk about it?

520
00:46:05,395 --> 00:46:08,228
I hope you won't become a
surgeon who prays in the O.R.

521
00:46:16,555 --> 00:46:17,829
Can we talk for a minute?

522
00:46:18,075 --> 00:46:19,349
We'll talk while camping.

523
00:46:19,595 --> 00:46:21,870
Jordan, I can't go camping now.

524
00:46:22,115 --> 00:46:23,753
We need some time together.

525
00:46:24,795 --> 00:46:27,389
All right, let's see if we can
just spend 5 minutes.

526
00:46:27,635 --> 00:46:30,707
Let's see if we can just stand
still together for 5 minutes.

527
00:46:31,555 --> 00:46:32,431
Doing what?

528
00:46:32,875 --> 00:46:34,593
Just being here.

529
00:46:35,955 --> 00:46:37,593
I'll get the trail map.

530
00:46:38,115 --> 00:46:39,150
No, I mean it.

531
00:46:39,635 --> 00:46:40,863
Nothing but us.

532
00:46:44,195 --> 00:46:45,423
What do I do?

533
00:46:46,835 --> 00:46:48,154
Just look at me.

534
00:46:59,795 --> 00:47:00,830
You can't do it.

535
00:47:02,715 --> 00:47:04,307
You can't do it.

536
00:47:04,555 --> 00:47:07,069
-You flinched. You lose!
